Below we set R_S ≡ 2GM and introduce the “tortoise” coordinate
 r* = r + R_S ln(r/R_S − 1),
the null‐coordinates
 u = t − r*, v = t + r*,
and define the Kruskal–Szekeres null coördinates
 U = − e^{−u/(2R_S)}, V = + e^{ v/(2R_S)}.
We then have the key identity
 e^{(v−u)/(2·2GM)} = e^{r*/R_S}
 = e^{r/R_S}\,(r/R_S − 1)
 = (r/R_S − 1)\,e^{r/R_S}\,,
so
1 − R_S/r 
= (r/R_S − 1)\,(R_S/r)
= (R_S/r)\,e^{−r/R_S}\;e^{(v−u)/(2·2GM)}.

Define the “regular” prefactor
 f(r) ≡ (R_S/r)\,e^{−r/R_S},
which is finite (nonzero) at r = R_S.  Then

 1 − 2GM/r  =  f(r)\;e^{(v−u)/(4GM)}.

Plugging this into the t–r part of Schwarzschild,
 ds²ₜᵣ = −(1 − 2GM/r)\,du dv
we get
 ds²ₜᵣ = −f(r)\,e^{(v−u)/(4GM)} du dv.

We may further trade (u,v) for (U,V).  Noting
 dU dV = −\,e^{(v−u)/(4GM)}/(16 G²M²)\;du dv
and f(r) = (2GM/r)e^{−r/(2GM)}, one finds the familiar Kruskal form

 ds²ₜᵣ = −\,{32 G³M³\over r}\,e^{−r/(2GM)}\;dU\,dV.

Boxing the two main results:

\[
\boxed{
1 - \frac{2GM}{r}
\;=\;
\underbrace{\bigl(\tfrac{2GM}{r}\bigr)e^{-\,r/(2GM)}}_{f(r)\neq0\;\text{at}\;r=2GM}
\;\times\;
e^{(v - u)/(4GM)}
\quad\longrightarrow\quad
ds^2_{tr}
\,=\;
-\,f(r)\,e^{(v-u)/(4GM)}\,du\,dv
}\]

\[
\boxed{
\phantom{1 - \tfrac{2GM}{r}}
\;\longrightarrow\;
ds^2_{tr}
\,=\;
-\,\frac{32\,G^3M^3}{r}\,e^{-r/(2GM)}\,dU\,dV
}
\]

Confidence: 85%
